<p>Helen De Cruz, professor of philosophy at Saint Louis University, has died.<span id="more-54137"></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-54140 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-1024x674.jpg" alt="" width="751" height="494" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-1024x674.jpg 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-300x197.jpg 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-768x505.jpg 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-1536x1011.jpg 1536w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-2048x1348.jpg 2048w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/de-cruz-helen-photo-400x263.jpg 400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 751px) 100vw, 751px" /></p>
<p><a href="https://helendecruz.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Professor De Cruz</a> specialized in philosophy of religion and cognitive science. They were the author of <a href="https://press.princeton.edu/books/hardcover/9780691232126/wonderstruck" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Wonderstruck: How Wonder and Awe Shape the Way We Think</em></a> (2024) and <a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/religious-disagreement/18A9B767E64FA47F97CD8E9814233210" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Religious Disagreement</em></a> (2018), and, along with Johan De Smedt, <a href="https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262028547/a-natural-history-of-natural-theology/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>A Natural History of Natural Theology: The Cognitive Science of Theology and Philosophy of Religion </em></a>(2014) and <a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/challenge-of-evolution-to-religion/E694F7F8FC0842F66FF685E5E9CBC7AA" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Challenge of Evolution to Religion</em></a> (2020), among other works. You can learn more about their writing <a href="https://helendecruz.net/education_research.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a> and <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/helen-de-cruz" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.</p>
<p>Professor De Cruz worked to expand the boundaries of philosophy beyond its standard academic formats, extending philosophical thinking into art, literature, and music. They were a talented artist, creating the illustrations for forty-two thought experiments in the popular book <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Philosophy-Illustrated-Helen-Cruz/dp/0190080531?crid=29QGEHBHM02QT&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.KnYDa5_eljizD9OKOR8KhKx1mPT4y1MYmJmxtGpjfaSbpmpB8GB1UNQbybGk__ILCyhl2QNg2ZydlQZjqqpUeR8XtcJoio2E5A-BAvjyt3RFhMCzFbLdl_Dwu0H-SWR1t1y2RuwYVCQkLE1y7M4sdPrBblo9Q7qRsMzi_EvGg4WCygTr5nmcWJFsThLxZJ9gOZ7CzzjAWVHkfbLba-Ro3O9mHNBm6fpFZuJWtEIfQW8.zlX6B5MNcSEu8Mx0hjXbRwryfQqx2RmMArv4zk4drhQ&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=philosophy+illustrated&amp;qid=1750262126&amp;sprefix=philosophy+illustrated%2Caps%2C121&amp;sr=8-1&amp;linkCode=ll1&amp;tag=dainou-20&amp;linkId=8c9b875e231236d414b5d397a4476c59&amp;language=en_US&amp;ref_=as_li_ss_tl" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Philosophy Illustrated</em></a> (2021). They wrote philosophical fiction, including <a href="https://thepinkhydra.itch.io/artistry" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Artistry of Magic</em></a> (2025), and many short stories (and co-edited a <a href="https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/philosophy-through-science-fiction-stories-9781350081239/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">collection</a> philosophical science fiction stories). They produced a video summary of Margaret Cavendish’s <a href="https://helendecruz.substack.com/p/illustrated-edition-of-margaret-cavendish" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Blazing World</em></a>, for which they also produced the illustrations and music. De Cruz published many essays in popular media outlets and at their newsletter, <a href="https://helendecruz.substack.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Wondering Freely</em></a>. They were extremely active in the philosophical community on social media, and were a longtime contributor to <a href="https://philosopherscocoon.typepad.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Philosophers&#8217; Cocoon</em></a>. In many ways, they showed how to express philosophical ideas in new forms via new avenues to new audiences.</p>
<p>De Cruz joined the faculty at Saint Louis University in 2019. Prior to that, they taught at Oxford Brookes University and VU Amsterdam. They earned a PhD in philosophy from the University of Groningen, and a PhD in archeology from the Free University of Brussels. You can learn more about them at their <a href="https://helendecruz.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">website</a>. An autobiographical interview with De Cruz can be found <a href="https://www.whatisitliketobeaphilosopher.com/helen-de-cruz" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.</p>
<p>She died on Friday, June 20th, 2025.</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"><em>by Eric Steinhart</em></p>
